commodity narrative:
Cheese makers are receiving more milk this week, as bottlers have decreased their milk orders. A few operations are running full up until the holiday. Some plants will be shut down, but they will restart the following day. Cheese production is fairly strong in the East currently. Inventories are steady to increasing due to more milk available in the region. Retail demand is fairly stable. Moreover, grocers are actively promoting holiday advertisements. Trading activity is steady to lower as many market participants' needs are met for the end of the year. In the Northeast, wholesale cheese prices for cheddar and Muenster shifted up by $0.0075, moreover process cheese prices moved up by $0.0075. The Grade A Swiss price is unchanged this week.

Cheese sales managers report orders from pizzerias for mozzarella and provolone cheese are good. Cheese supplies in the East are adequate to fill all contract requests at this time. Trading activity for cheddar cheese is steady to lower. Cheddar cheese spot prices are steady to decreased as some buyers are not purchasing on the spot market. The DMN Northeast November 2018 monthly average price for cheddar blocks is $2.0230, compared to $2.2157 one month ago. Processed 5# sliced average price is $1.6748, compared to $1.7166 one month ago. In the Northeast, wholesale cheese prices for cheddar and Muenster shifted down by $0.0075, however process cheese prices moved up by $0.0075. The Grade A Swiss price is unchanged this week.

This week, a cooperative export assistance program accepted requests for export assistance to sell 4.028 million pounds (1,827 metric tons) of cheese.
methodology: Information for the period December 3 - 7, 2018, issued weekly

commodity narrative:
Cheese production is stable to slightly lower this week. Coming off the holiday, milk availability for Class III is lower, as Class I demand has increased as schools reopened. Moreover, some market participants report poor feed quality is affecting milk output off some Northeastern farms. Cheese makers relay regular food service orders for mozzarella and provolone cheese are good. Overall cheese inventories in the East are fairly steady at this time. There are some reports of higher cheese supplies in parts of the U.S. currently, due to lower international orders. Spot market prices for cheddar cheese are somewhat mixed on various pricing indices. Trading activity is stable to decreased as some buyers are waiting to see where spot prices go. commodity narrative:
Milk production in the Northeast is level this week. Frigid weather conditions are lingering in parts of the region, causing slower travel time on the roads. However, there are little to no reports of major transportation disruptions or power outages at this time. Currently, milk volumes are steady to becoming more available, as most Class I needs are met this week. There are some reports of cheese makers adding additional milk loads into the plants. Although a couple manufacturers are closed for Thanksgiving, they will run longer production schedules for a few days after the holiday. Mozzarella and provolone cheese orders are working well through food service contracts. Cheddar cheese orders from retailers are stable. Grocers are heavily advertising holiday cheese discounts. Cheddar cheese trading activity is steady to quiet this week due to market participants having adequate supplies. Cheddar spot prices are lower on various pricing indices. In the Northeast, wholesale cheese prices for cheddar and Muenster shifted down by $0.0225, however process cheese prices moved up by $0.0225. The Grade A Swiss price is steady this week.

commodity narrative:
Northeast milk production is flat in some areas and slightly increasing in other areas, overall taking a toll on milk availability in the region. In general, milk is in good balance in the Northeast, as loads are securing homes without tolling or cream separation. Milk volumes clearing into Class III are higher this week as other Class' needs are slightly down. Mozzarella and provolone production are fairly steady, and orders are very good from retail and food service sectors. Cheddar cheese production is stable and retail orders are steady to increased as grocers are gearing up for holiday advertisements. Moreover, there are reports of increased cheese consumption in the U.S. than in past years. Cheese supplies are stable in the region, and some cheese makers would like to grow their inventories in the near future. Spot trading is currently lower, and prices fluctuate on various indices this week. In the Northeast, wholesale cheese prices for cheddar and Muenster shifted down by $0.0750, and process cheese prices moved lower by $0.0650. The Grade A Swiss price is steady this week.

Cheese supplies are stable in the region, and some cheese makers would like to grow their inventories in the near future. Spot trading is currently lower, and prices fluctuate on various indices this week. In the Northeast, wholesale cheese prices for cheddar and Muenster shifted down by $0.0750, and process cheese prices moved lower by $0.0650. The Grade A Swiss price is steady this week.

commodity narrative:
Repair and maintenance workloads at certain eastern cheese processing facilities prevented those plants to be operated at full capacity this week. Furthermore, Class III milk intakes are steady to somewhat lower. As the result, cheese output in the Northeast has remained stable to decreasing. Swiss cheese is not as much manufactured this week due to limited milk availability. Mozzarella and provolone sales have picked up with the pizza season and the resuming of school terms. Retailers and restaurant managers are also taking in more cheese. Overall, cheese stocks are in good balance with current industry needs. In the Northeast, wholesale cheese prices for cheddar and Muenster shifted up by $0.0400, but process cheese prices moved lower by $0.0125. The Grade A Swiss price is unchanged from last week.

The DMN Northeast September 2018 monthly average price for cheddar blocks is $2.2438, compared to $2.1854 one year ago. Processed 5# sliced average price is $1.8889, compared to $1.9269 one year ago.

commodity narrative:
Northeast milk production is slightly level on the farms this week. Intermittent hot and humid weather conditions continue to take a toll on cow comfort. Milk volumes clearing into cheese vats are steady to lower, as other Class needs are being met at this time. Mozzarella and provolone cheese production is fairly active. Regular orders have improved with the opening of educational institutions. Fresh cheese supplies are somewhat limited as the demand is keeping inventories stable. There are reports of some operations having adequate supplies of cheese that were made earlier in the year. Trading activity for 40-pound block cheddar cheese is steady to lower. However, barrel cheddar cheese spot trading is steady. Spot prices have decreased and some manufacturers are offering barrels on the spot market. The wholesale prices for cheddar and Muenster declined $0.0500. Also, the process cheese price shifted down $0.1150. The Grade A Swiss price is steady this week.

commodity narrative:
Milk into cheese vats is steady to lower, as milk production continues to decline and bottlers are in high demand for milk supplies. Moreover, the Northeast is facing very hot and humid weather, overall negatively impacting cow comfort. Cheese production is stable to lower. Mozzarella cheese orders are strong as college campuses have reopened for the school year. Consumer retail demand is currently strong as customers are purchasing cheese from grocers at a discount. Manufacturers’ cheese supplies are steady to shorter, as the cheese coming right out of the brine water into packaging is limited. The day after the holiday, cheddar cheese barrel spot market activity was strong. Spot market prices for block and barrel cheddar cheese are steady to higher. The wholesale prices for cheddar and Muenster increased $0.0350. In addition, the process cheese price shifted up $0.0275. The Grade A Swiss price increased $0.0025 this week following the release of the August 2018 Announcement of Class and Component Prices. Additionally, the Class III skim milk price for August 2018 saw a 62 cents incline. The DMN Northeast August 2018 monthly average price for cheddar blocks is $2.1960, compared to $2.3013 one year ago. Processed 5# sliced average price is $1.9210, compared to $1.9870 one year ago.

Moreover, there are reports of some Northeast milk being transported to the Southeast, as schools’ pipelines are still being filled. Cheese production is steady to decreased as production schedules are running, but with lower milk volumes. Cheddar cheese orders from grocers are stable to increasing, as customers get ready for the Labor Day holiday. Provolone cheese demand is fairly steady, as retail sectors are seeing a stable consumer economy. Mozzarella cheese interest is stable to growing as educational institutions are gearing up for increasing pizza consumption. Cheese inventories are fairly steady, yet current fresh supplies are somewhat limited. Spot trading activity is steady as prices have increased, although some market participants will wait to see where cheese prices go. The wholesale prices for cheddar and Muenster declined $0.0200. In addition, the process cheese price decreased $0.0775. The Grade A Swiss price is steady this week.

commodity narrative: Milk production is level to slightly lower this week in the Northeast. Cheese makers in the area report receiving enough milk for full cheese production. The demand for cheese is picking up in the United States. Cheddar and provolone cheese interest in retail and restaurant sectors is fairly stable as orders have increased. Mozzarella demand has strengthened as educational institutions are resupplying their inventories for the new school year. Cheese stocks are steady to higher, as cheese production in the Northeast is active. Spot trading is steady to light as many market participants are working through contracts and are seeing where the spot prices lead. The wholesale prices for cheddar and Muenster increased $0.0250. However, the process cheese price is unchanged. The Grade A Swiss price increased $0.0800 following the release of the July 2018 Announcement of Class and Component Prices. Overall, the Class III skim milk price for July 2018 saw a 64 cent decline. The DMN Northeast July 2018 monthly average price for cheddar blocks is $2.1317, compared to $2.1900 one year ago. Processed 5# sliced average price is $1.7167, compared to $1.8060 one year ago.
secondary source info:
The CME Group July 2018 monthly average price for barrels was $1.3707, compared to $1.4396 a year ago; blocks’ average price was $1.5364, down from $1.6586 a year ago.

commodity narrative: Milk production is level to slightly lower this week in the Northeast. Cheese makers in the area report receiving enough milk for full cheese production. The demand for cheese is picking up in the United States. Cheddar and provolone cheese interest in retail and restaurant sectors is fairly stable as orders have increased. Mozzarella demand has strengthened as educational institutions are resupplying their inventories for the new school year. Cheese stocks are steady to higher, as cheese production in the Northeast is active. Spot trading is steady to light as many market participants are working through contracts and are seeing where the spot prices lead. The wholesale prices for cheddar and Muenster increased $0.0250. However, the process cheese price is unchanged. The Grade A Swiss price increased $0.0800 following the release of the July 2018 Announcement of Class and Component Prices. Overall, the Class III skim milk price for July 2018 saw a 64 cent decline. The DMN Northeast July 2018 monthly average price for cheddar blocks is $2.1317, compared to $2.1900 one year ago. Processed 5# sliced average price is $1.7167, compared to $1.8060 one year ago.

Northeast milk production is down as the heat continues to engulf the area. Although there have been reports of harsh downpours in the Northeast, market participants do not indicate any weather related interferences with transportation or cheese production schedules. Cheese makers report receiving enough milk to run at full production. There are reports of domestic cheese demand picking up. Cheddar and provolone cheese interest in retail and restaurant sectors is stable, as grocers are advertising 8-ounce cheddar cheese at a discount and restaurants’ provolone orders are fairly strong. Mozzarella demand has increased as educational institutions are resupplying their inventories for the start of school. Although cheese demand is higher, overall cheese inventories are steady to higher, as Northeast cheese production is strong. Cheddar cheese spot market activity is steady to somewhat quiet as many market participant are waiting to see where the cheese prices lead. The wholesale prices for cheddar and Muenster decreased $0.0200. However, the process cheese price shifted higher $0.0975. The Grade A Swiss prices are steady this week.

Even with shorter regional milk volumes, many cheese plants are clearing milk supplies near to capacity for processing needs. Provolone and cheddar cheese orders are steady to slightly picking up as market participants report customers’ demands are marginally increasing after much trade concern. Mozzarella demand is currently slow, but cheese makers report orders will increase once educational institutions are back in session. Overall cheese inventories are long, yet with lower milk production, a few reports suggest fresh cheese supplies are shorter. Spot market cheddar cheese block and barrel prices are steady to lower and sales activity is fairly steady. The cheese market is still showing signs of concern, however market participants are aware of the current situation and are working through new contracts. The wholesale prices for cheddar and Muenster decreased $0.0050. However, the process cheese price shifted up $0.0275. The Grade A Swiss prices are steady this week.

The wholesale prices for cheddar and Muenster decreased $0.0050. However, the process cheese price shifted up $0.0275. The Grade A Swiss prices are steady this week.

commodity narrative: Milk volumes are available in the Northeast for strong cheese processing. Cheese makers report they are clearing milk loads into vats at close to plant capacity levels to handle milk supplies before the holiday. However, some operations will be open all week as production schedules are full. Cheddar cheese inventories are stable to increasing. The demand for cheddar in the retail sector is steady to increased this week, as the July 4 holiday increased grocers’ cheese advertisements. Mozzarella and provolone supplies are steady to growing as interest is somewhat slower currently. Spot market conditions have gained some strength back this week as prices are higher, yet with much concern over the demand for U.S. exports and the shortened trading week, buyers are taking a wait and see approach to the current market. The process cheese price declined $0.0425. Also, the wholesale prices for cheddar and Muenster decreased $0.0375. The Grade A Swiss price is unchanged. The DMN Northeast June 2018 monthly average price for cheddar blocks is $2.1888, compared to $2.2350 one year ago. Processed 5# sliced average price is $1.8551, compared to $1.8231 one year ago.
secondary source info:
The CME Group June 2018 monthly average price for barrels was $1.4145, compared to $1.3972 a year ago; blocks’ average price was $1.5617, down from $1.6022 a year ago.

commodity narrative: Milk intake into cheese vats is slightly lower as some contacts report plants are down this week for new projects. Overall, spot milk remains abundant in the area. Cheese production is steady. Provolone and mozzarella are running at full production, despite slower demand from schools and the restaurant industry. Italian cheese inventories are long and increasing, waiting for the school year to pick up in August. The recent trade news from China have concerned some contacts about how the cheese market will be affected. The spot market activity is bearish, with block and barrel prices dropping significantly moving into the week on the CME, and the price gap increasing. The process cheese price decreased $0.0075. Moreover, the wholesale prices for cheddar and Muenster increased $0.0225. The Grade A Swiss price is unchanged.

commodity narrative:
Milk volumes in the Northeast are heavy and putting some pressure on cheese plants. Some operations’ production schedules are shortened for maintenance and their operations are not able to take in as much milk this week. Overall, cheese facilities are at lower to full capacity. Cheddar cheese processing is stable to a tad lower as production needs are decreased. Provolone and mozzarella production are steady and strong as milk is readily available. General cheese supplies are steady to growing. The demand for cheddar and mozzarella is steady to somewhat slowed down, however sliced provolone demand is currently stable. Spot market activity is steady to slightly increased as cheese barrels had some uptick in interest. With some international markets changing trading regulations, many market participants anticipate a change in general market cheese prices. The process cheese price decreased $0.0225. Moreover, the wholesale price for cheddar and Muenster declined $0.0125. The Grade A Swiss price is unchanged.

commodity narrative:
Northeast cheese makers are receiving high milk levels into their intakes. Production schedules are running at to near capacity. Cheddar production is strong and market participants report they are clearing extra milk loads. Cheddar cheese interest from retail sectors is fairly steady. Mozzarella and provolone production are steady as milk is available for production needs. The demand for contract orders of provolone sliced cheese is stable. Mozzarella orders are steady to slow as educational institutions are closing for the summer. Overall cheese inventories are stable to increasing. Cheddar block and barrel cheese trading activities and pricing are mixed. Some pricing indices’ prices and activity are higher and active, although other spot trades and prices are lower. The process cheese price decreased $0.0125. In addition, the wholesale price for cheddar and Muenster declined $0.0200. The Grade A Swiss price increased $0.0925 following the release of the May 2018 Announcement of Class and Component Prices. Additionally, the Class III skim milk price for May 2018 saw a 32 cents increase. The DMN Northeast May 2018 monthly average price for cheddar blocks is $2.2388, compared to $2.1890 one year ago. Processed 5# sliced average price is $1.9476, compared to $1.8390 one year ago.

Mozzarella orders are steady to slow as educational institutions are closing for the summer. Overall cheese inventories are stable to increasing. Cheddar block and barrel cheese trading activities and pricing are mixed. Some pricing indices’ prices and activity are higher and active, although other spot trades and prices are lower. The process cheese price decreased $0.0125. In addition, the wholesale price for cheddar and Muenster declined $0.0200. The Grade A Swiss price increased $0.0925 following the release of the May 2018 Announcement of Class and Component Prices. Additionally, the Class III skim milk price for May 2018 saw a 32 cents increase. The DMN Northeast May 2018 monthly average price for cheddar blocks is $2.2388, compared to $2.1890 one year ago. Processed 5# sliced average price is $1.9476, compared to $1.8390 one year ago.

commodity narrative: Milk inventories are currently higher in the Northeast. Cheese makers are receiving heavy milk loads, and production schedules are at near to full capacity. Moreover, some market participants report more pressure to take extra milk loads when there is a local oversupply. Cheddar cheese processing is fairly steady and inventories are stable to increasing. Cheddar cheese demand from retail stores is steady to a tad higher as the holiday kicked off the grilling season. Provolone and mozzarella production are stable. There are reports of stable sliced provolone orders, but mozzarella orders are a bit slower as schools are letting out for the summer. Spot market activity is steady to slower on a shorter trading week. The process cheese price shifted down $0.0125. However, the wholesale price for cheddar and Muenster increased $0.0200. The Grade A Swiss price is unchanged. National Retail Report-Dairy, for May 25-31, 2018, noted the U.S. weighted average advertised price for 8 ounce cheese block was $2.13, down 23 cents from the previous week, but up 6 cents from last year. The U.S. weighted average advertised price of 8 ounce cheese shreds was $2.14, a decrease of 14 cents from last week, and down 5 cents from a year ago. Northeast region’s weighted average advertised price for 8 ounce cheese blocks was $2.28, 15 cents above the U.S. average, with a regional price range of $1.50-$3.50. The average price for 8 oz. cheese shreds was $2.26, 12 cents above the national average, with prices ranging $1.99-$3.49. In the Southeast region, the average price for 8 oz. cheese blocks was $2.15, 2 cents above the average U.S. price, with a regional price range of $1.50-$2.98. The average price for 8 oz. shreds was $2.13, 1 cent below the U.S. average, with prices ranging $1.50-$2.98.

commodity narrative: Milk production is climbing in the Northeast currently. Market participants report heavy amounts of milk are clearing into Class III production, although cheese makers inform they are not feeling too pressured to take extra milk loads. Cheddar cheese production is strong, and mozzarella and provolone cheese production are stable. Generally, cheese plants are running at or near capacity. Cheese inventories are steady to increasing and restaurant contract orders are at seasonal levels. Spot market activity is mixed. Prices for spot cheddar block and barrel cheese are steady to higher this week. Moreover, cheddar barrels had an uptick in sales on the CME Group exchange. The process cheese price shifted lower $0.0750. In addition, the wholesale price for cheddar and Muenster decreased $0.0700. The Grade A Swiss price is steady. National Retail Report-Dairy, for May 18-24, 2018, noted the U.S. weighted average advertised price for 8 ounce cheese block was $2.36, up 10 cents from the previous week, and up 10 cents from last year. The U.S. weighted average advertised price of 8 ounce cheese shreds was $2.28, an increase of 10 cents from last week, and up 10 cents from a year ago. Northeast region’s weighted average advertised price for 8 ounce cheese blocks was $2.39, 3 cents above the U.S. average, with a regional price range of $1.77-$3.00. The average price for 8 oz. cheese shreds was $2.39, 11 cents above the national average, with prices ranging $1.77-$3.49. In the Southeast region, the average price for 8 oz. cheese blocks was $2.34, 2 cents below the average U.S. price, with a regional price range of $1.88-$3.00. The average price for 8 oz. shreds was $2.16, 12 cents below the U.S. average, with prices ranging $1.88-$2.50.
secondary source info: COLD STORAGE:  According to NASS, U.S. stocks of total natural cheese as of April 2018 totaled 1.3 billion pounds, 2 percent higher than the previous month, and up 3 percent from a year ago. Swiss cheese totaled 29.2 million pounds, 8 percent higher than a year ago, and no change in percent from last month. In New England, stocks of American cheese totaled 66.9 million pounds, 1 percent lower than April 2017, but up 1 percent from March 2018.
methodology: Information for the period May 21 - 25, 2018, issued weekly

Northeast region’s weighted average advertised price for 8 ounce cheese blocks was $2.31, 5 cents above the U.S. average, with a regional price range of $1.88-$3.29. The average price for 8 oz. cheese shreds was $2.15, 3 cents below the national average, with prices ranging $1.77-$3.00. Routine orders from restaurants are good. There are reports of increased cheddar cheese prices in some international markets. Domestic cheese spot trading activities have been steady to somewhat light this week. The process cheese price shifted higher $0.0050. National Retail Report-Dairy, for April 27-May 3, 2018, noted the U.S. weighted average advertised price for 8 ounce cheese block was $2.24, up 2 cents from the previous week and up 23 cents from last year. The U.S. weighted average advertised price of 8 ounce cheese shreds was $2.21, a decrease of 6 cents from last week, but up 13 cents from a year ago. Northeast region’s weighted average advertised price for 8 ounce cheese blocks was $2.23, 1 cent below the U.S. average, with a regional price range of $1.67-$3.00. The average price for 8 oz. cheese shreds was $2.31, 10 cents above the national average, with prices ranging $1.88-$3.00. In the Southeast region, the average price for 8 oz. cheese blocks was $2.47, 23 cents above the average U.S. price, with a regional price range of $2.00-$2.50. The average price for 8 oz. shreds was $2.24, 3 cents above the U.S. average, with prices ranging $1.66-$3.00.

commodity narrative: Milk is ticking up in the Northeast, as spring flush has arrived and warmer temperatures are making their way into the area. Although increased milk volumes are clearing into manufacturing facilities, cheese processors are managing very well. Manufacturers’ supplies are fairly steady. Regular orders from restaurant and retail sectors are good. Cheddar 40 pound block spot activities are mixed this week, as some markets have been somewhat quiet. Cheese barrel spot trading is pretty steady and there are some reports of more available barrel spot loads than 40 pound block spot loads. The process cheese price shifted higher $0.0100. However, the wholesale price for cheddar and Muenster is unchanged. In addition, the Grade A Swiss price is unchanged. National Retail Report-Dairy, for April 20-26, 2018, noted the U.S. weighted average advertised price for 8 ounce cheese block was $2.22, up 16 cents from the previous week and up 3 cents from last year. The U.S. weighted average advertised price of 8 ounce cheese shreds was $2.27, a decrease of 1 cent from last week, but up 8 cents from a year ago. Northeast region’s weighted average advertised price for 8 ounce cheese blocks was $2.44, 22 cents above the U.S. average, with a regional price range of $1.50-$3.69. The average price for 8 oz. cheese shreds was $2.29, 2 cents above the national average, with prices ranging $1.50-$3.49. In the Southeast region, the average price for 8 oz. cheese blocks was $1.97, 25 cents below the average U.S. price, with a regional price range of $1.67-$2.50. The average price for 8 oz. shreds was $2.27, the same price as the U.S. average, with prices ranging $1.67-$2.50.
secondary source info:
This week, a cooperative export assistance program accepted requests for export assistance to sell 881,849 pounds (400 metric tons) of cheese. 

COLD STORAGE:  According to NASS, U.S. stocks of total natural cheese as of March 31, 2018 totaled 1.3 billion pounds, 1 percent more than the previous month, and up 5 percent from a year ago. Swiss cheese totaled 29.1 million pounds, 12 percent higher than a year ago, and up 4 percent from last month. In New England, stocks of American cheese totaled 65.9 million pounds, 2 percent lower than March 2017, but 1 percent higher than February 2018.

commodity narrative: Harsh accumulations of snow and rain with gusty winds hovered over some areas in the Eastern region this week. Major roadways were closed, but there have not been many reports of milk transportation delays. Northeast cheese production is close to full capacity as more available milk loads are being cleared into intakes. Inventories are in pretty decent shape as manufacturers report mozzarella and provolone retail orders are good. Domestic cheddar cheese spot prices are fairly steady and cheddar barrel spot sales seem to have more activity this week compared to past weeks and some export cheddar trading prices have increased. Cheddar barrels seemed to garner more interest than cheddar blocks this week. The wholesale price for cheddar and Muenster increased $0.0625. In addition, the process cheese price shifted higher $0.0225. The Grade A Swiss price is unchanged. National Retail Report-Dairy, for April 13-19, 2018, noted the U.S. weighted average advertised price for 8 ounce cheese block was $2.06, up 19 cents from the previous week, but down 26 cents from last year. The U.S. weighted average advertised price of 8 ounce cheese shreds was $2.28, an increase of 35 cents from last week, but down 3 cents from a year ago. Northeast region’s weighted average advertised price for 8 ounce cheese blocks was $2.57, 51 cents above the U.S. average, with a regional price range of $1.99-$3.00. The average price for 8 oz. cheese shreds was $2.59, 31 cents above the national average, with prices ranging $1.99-$3.00. In the Southeast region, the average price for 8 oz. cheese blocks was $2.04, 2 cents below the average U.S. price, with a regional price range of $1.67-$2.50. The average price for 8 oz. shreds was $2.63, 35 cents above the U.S. average, with prices ranging $1.67-$3.00.

Domestic cheddar cheese spot prices are fairly steady and cheddar barrel spot sales seem to have more activity this week compared to past weeks and some export cheddar trading prices have increased. Cheddar barrels seemed to garner more interest than cheddar blocks this week. The wholesale price for cheddar and Muenster increased $0.0625. In addition, the process cheese price shifted higher $0.0225. The Grade A Swiss price is unchanged. National Retail Report-Dairy, for April 13-19, 2018, noted the U.S. weighted average advertised price for 8 ounce cheese block was $2.06, up 19 cents from the previous week, but down 26 cents from last year. The U.S. weighted average advertised price of 8 ounce cheese shreds was $2.28, an increase of 35 cents from last week, but down 3 cents from a year ago. Northeast region’s weighted average advertised price for 8 ounce cheese blocks was $2.57, 51 cents above the U.S. average, with a regional price range of $1.99-$3.00. The average price for 8 oz. cheese shreds was $2.59, 31 cents above the national average, with prices ranging $1.99-$3.00. In the Southeast region, the average price for 8 oz. cheese blocks was $2.04, 2 cents below the average U.S. price, with a regional price range of $1.67-$2.50. The average price for 8 oz. shreds was $2.63, 35 cents above the U.S. average, with prices ranging $1.67-$3.00.

commodity narrative: Northeast market participants report milk production is slightly increasing, as warmer weather is trying to make its way to the region. With bottling orders still down, available milk loads are clearing into more manufacturing intakes. Cheese processing is steady and contract orders are fairly firm. Pricing indices are mixed, yet cheese spot sales are quite moderate this week. The wholesale price for cheddar and Muenster decreased $0.0225. In addition, the process cheese price shifted lower $0.0425. The Grade A Swiss price is steady. The DMN Northeast March 2018 monthly average price for cheddar blocks is $2.1559, compared to $2.0529 one year ago. Processed 5# sliced average price is $1.8811, compared to $1.8099 one year ago. The CME Group March 2018 monthly average price for barrels was $1.5071, compared to $1.4072 a year ago; blocks’ average price was $1.5614, compared to $1.4342 a year ago. This week, a cooperative export assistance program accepted 11 requests for export assistance to sell 2.017 million pounds (915 metric tons) of cheese. National Retail Report-Dairy, for March 30-April 5, 2018, noted the U.S. weighted average advertised price for 8 ounce cheese block was $2.02, down 15 cents from the previous week and down 17 cents from last year. The U.S. weighted average advertised price of 8 ounce cheese shreds was $2.06, an increase of 3 cents from last week, but down 14 cents from a year ago. Northeast region’s weighted average advertised price for 8 ounce cheese blocks was $1.91, 11 cents below the U.S. average, with a regional price range of $0.99-$2.00. The average price for 8 oz. cheese shreds was $2.03, 3 cents below the national average, with prices ranging $0.99-$3.00. In the Southeast region, the average price for 8 oz. cheese blocks was $1.95, 7 cents below the average U.S. price, with a regional price range of $1.66-$3.00. The average price for 8 oz. shreds was $1.96, 10 cents below the U.S. average, with prices ranging $1.66-$2.50.

Class I orders are lower in the East, thus milk is clearing heavily into Class III intakes. Cheese production is strong and manufacturers report orders are fairly good. The U.S. weighted average advertised price of 8 ounce cheese shreds was $2.03, a decrease of 20 cents from last week and down 8 cents from a year ago. Northeast region’s weighted average advertised price for 8 ounce cheese blocks was $2.30, 13 cents above the U.S. average, with a regional price range of $0.99-$3.00. The average price for 8 oz. cheese shreds was $2.02, 1 cent below the national average, with prices ranging $0.99-$2.99. In the Southeast region, the average price for 8 oz. cheese blocks was $2.03, 14 cents below the average U.S. price, with a regional price range of $1.66-$3.00. In New England, stocks of American cheese totaled 65.0 million pounds, 1 percent lower than February 2017, but 3 percent higher from January 2018.

commodity narrative: This week, severe snowstorm conditions hit parts of the Northeast. Although, the blizzard had an effect on some transportation issues and power outages, Northeast cheese makers report they are receiving all of the milk they need for full production. Mozzarella and provolone processing schedules are full and orders are currently good. Cheddar cheese production is active and inventories are stable to slightly growing. Current spot sale activities are steady to fairly quiet for cheese barrels and 40-pound blocks. The wholesale price for cheddar and Muenster increased $0.0475. The process cheese price shifted higher $0.0375. The Grade A Swiss price is unchanged. At Tuesday’s CME Group trading, daily cash prices saw barrels close at $1.5000, down $0.0150, and blocks closed at $1.5400, a decrease of $0.0625 from last Tuesday. National Retail Report-Dairy, for March 9-15, 2018, noted the U.S. weighted average advertised price for 8 ounce cheese block was $2.19, down 8 cents from the previous week and down 6 cents from last year. The U.S. weighted average advertised price of 8 ounce cheese shreds was $2.16, a decrease of 4 cents from last week and down 15 cents from a year ago. Northeast region’s weighted average advertised price for 8 ounce cheese blocks was $2.16, 3 cents below the U.S. average, with a regional price range of $1.29-$3.00. The average price for 8 oz. cheese shreds was $2.12, down 4 cents from the national average, with prices ranging $1.29-$3.00. In the Southeast region, the average price for 8 oz. cheese blocks was $2.14, 5 cents above the average U.S. price, with a regional price range of $1.66-$3.00. The average price for 8 oz. shreds was $2.06, 10 cents below the U.S. average, with prices ranging $1.66-$2.50.

commodity narrative:
Milk volumes clearing to Northeastern cheese vats are mixed. There have been winter storms causing power outages and disruptions in milk haulers’ schedules. Despite the weather conditions, cheddar cheese production is strong and inventories are capable for current demand. Groceries are gearing up for the holiday by advertising cheese 8-32 ounce packages at discounts. This week, cheese 40-pound block and barrel spot sales are steady to lower. The wholesale price for cheddar and Muenster increased $0.0050. The process cheese price shifted lower $0.0075. The Grade A Swiss price declined $0.1600 following the release of the February 2018 Announcement of Class and Component Prices. Additionally, the Class III skim milk price for February 2018 saw a 24 cents decline. The CME Group February 2018 monthly average price for barrels was $1.4096, compared to $1.6230 a year ago; blocks’ average price was $1.5157, compared to $1.6199 a year ago. The DMN Northeast February 2018 monthly average price for cheddar blocks is $2.1029, compared to $2.2547 one year ago. Processed 5# sliced average price is $1.7517, compared to $1.9757 one year ago. At Tuesday’s CME Group trading, daily cash prices saw barrels close at $1.5150, up $0.0450, and blocks closed at $1.6025, an increase of $0.0725 from last Tuesday. National Retail Report-Dairy, for March 2-8, 2018, noted the U.S. weighted average advertised price for 8 ounce cheese block was $2.27, up 5 cents from the previous week and up 12 cents from last year. The U.S. weighted average advertised price of 8 ounce cheese shreds was $2.20, a decrease of 1 cent from last week and from a year ago. Northeast region’s weighted average advertised price for 8 ounce cheese blocks was $2.24, 3 cents below the U.S. average, with a regional price range of $1.29-$3.00. The average price for 8 oz. cheese shreds was $2.20, the same price as the  national average, with prices ranging $1.29-$3.00. In the Southeast region, the average price for 8 oz. cheese blocks was $2.35, 8 cents above the average U.S. price, with a regional price range of $1.67-$3.00. The average price for 8 oz. shreds was $2.17, 3 cents below the U.S. average, with prices ranging $1.67-$2.50. 
DAIRY PRODUCTS: According to NASS, U.S. total cheese production in January 2018 was 1.08 billion pounds, 3.4 percent higher than a year ago, but 1.0 percent lower than last month. In the Atlantic region, total cheese production was 137.3 million pounds, 2.8 percent higher than a year ago, but 1.3 percent lower than the previous month. Total cheese production and percentage change, from last year for selected Eastern states are, Pennsylvania 37.0 million pounds, +3.3 percent; Vermont 12.3 million pounds, +0.2 percent, and New Jersey 4.9 million pounds, +20.9 percent.

Groceries are gearing up for the holiday by advertising cheese 8-32 ounce packages at discounts. This week, cheese 40-pound block and barrel spot sales are steady to lower. The wholesale price for cheddar and Muenster increased $0.0050. The process cheese price shifted lower $0.0075. The Grade A Swiss price declined $0.1600 following the release of the February 2018 Announcement of Class and Component Prices. Additionally, the Class III skim milk price for February 2018 saw a 24 cents decline. The CME Group February 2018 monthly average price for barrels was $1.4096, compared to $1.6230 a year ago; blocks’ average price was $1.5157, compared to $1.6199 a year ago. The DMN Northeast February 2018 monthly average price for cheddar blocks is $2.1029, compared to $2.2547 one year ago. Processed 5# sliced average price is $1.7517, compared to $1.9757 one year ago. At Tuesday’s CME Group trading, daily cash prices saw barrels close at $1.5150, up $0.0450, and blocks closed at $1.6025, an increase of $0.0725 from last Tuesday. National Retail Report-Dairy, for March 2-8, 2018, noted the U.S. weighted average advertised price for 8 ounce cheese block was $2.27, up 5 cents from the previous week and up 12 cents from last year. The U.S. weighted average advertised price of 8 ounce cheese shreds was $2.20, a decrease of 1 cent from last week and from a year ago. Northeast region’s weighted average advertised price for 8 ounce cheese blocks was $2.24, 3 cents below the U.S. average, with a regional price range of $1.29-$3.00. The average price for 8 oz. cheese shreds was $2.20, the same price as the  national average, with prices ranging $1.29-$3.00. In the Southeast region, the average price for 8 oz. cheese blocks was $2.35, 8 cents above the average U.S. price, with a regional price range of $1.67-$3.00. The average price for 8 oz. shreds was $2.17, 3 cents below the U.S. average, with prices ranging $1.67-$2.50. 
DAIRY PRODUCTS: According to NASS, U.S. total cheese production in January 2018 was 1.08 billion pounds, 3.4 percent higher than a year ago, but 1.0 percent lower than last month. In the Atlantic region, total cheese production was 137.3 million pounds, 2.8 percent higher than a year ago, but 1.3 percent lower than the previous month. Total cheese production and percentage change, from last year for selected Eastern states are, Pennsylvania 37.0 million pounds, +3.3 percent; Vermont 12.3 million pounds, +0.2 percent, and New Jersey 4.9 million pounds, +20.9 percent.

commodity narrative:
Northeast milk availability is somewhat tight, as the winter conditions and feed quality have had an effect on production. Cheese production is active as milk clears into Class III, although some cheese makers are handling just enough milk loads for steady production. Cheese block trading on the spot market this week is steady to sluggish as prices have risen, however many buyers have not purchased from the heavy amount of offers. The Northeast wholesale cheddar and Muenster prices decreased $0.0500, and the process cheese price decreased $0.0250. The Grade A Swiss price increased $0.0200 following the release of the January 2018 Announcement of Class and Component Prices. Additionally, the Class III skim milk price for January 2108 saw a $1.34 decline. The CME Group January 2018 monthly average price for barrels was $1.3345, compared to $1.5573 a year ago; blocks’ average price was $1.4938, down from $1.6866 a year ago. The DMN Northeast January 2018 monthly average price for cheddar blocks is $2.1032, compared to $2.2893 one year ago. Processed 5# sliced average price is $1.7365, compared to $1.9511 one year ago. At Tuesday’s CME Group trading, daily cash prices saw barrels closed at $1.3700, up $0.0500, and blocks closed at $1.5175, increased $0.0550 from last Tuesday. This week, a cooperative export assistance program accepted requests for export assistance to sell 2.974 million pounds (1,349 metric tons) of cheese. The DMN National Retail Report-Dairy, for February 2-8, 2018, noted the U.S. weighted average advertised price for 8 ounce cheese block was $2.10, decreased 18 cents from the previous week and down 5 cents from last year. The U.S. weighted average advertised price of 8 ounce cheese shreds was $2.18, decreased 9 cents from last week and down 5 cents from a year ago. Northeast region’s weighted average advertised price for 8 ounce cheese blocks was $2.17, 7 cents above the U.S. average, with a regional price range of $1.66-$3.00. The Southeast region’s average price for 8 oz. cheese blocks was $2.13, 3 cents above the average U.S. price, with a regional price range of $1.66-$3.50. In the Northeast, the average price for 8 oz. cheese shreds was $2.25, 7 cents above the national average. In the Southeast, the average price for 8 oz. shreds was $1.94, 24 cents lower than the U.S. average, with prices ranging $1.66-$2.50. DAIRY PRODUCTS: According to NASS, U.S. total cheese production in December 2017 was 1.09 billion pounds, 2.6 percent higher than a year ago and 3.0 percent higher than last month. In the Atlantic region, total cheese production was 139.2 million pounds, 6.2 percent higher than a year ago, but 0.6 percent lower than the previous month. Total cheese production and percentage change, from last year for selected Eastern states, are New York 77.7 million pounds, +8.3 percent; Pennsylvania 35.0 million pounds, +1.5 percent; Vermont 12.8 million pounds, +5.1 percent, and New Jersey 5.4 million pounds, +2.0 percent.

commodity narrative:
Northeast milk availability is somewhat tight, as the winter conditions and feed quality have had an effect on production. Cheese production is active as milk clears into Class III, although some cheese makers are handling just enough milk loads for steady production. Cheese block trading on the spot market this week is steady to sluggish as prices have risen, however many buyers have not purchased from the heavy amount of offers. The Northeast wholesale cheddar and Muenster prices decreased $0.0500, and the process cheese price decreased $0.0250. The Grade A Swiss price increased $0.0200 following the release of the January 2018 Announcement of Class and Component Prices. Additionally, the Class III skim milk price for January 2108 saw a $1.34 decline. The CME Group January 2018 monthly average price for barrels was $1.3345, compared to $1.5573 a year ago; blocks’ average price was $1.4938, down from $1.6866 a year ago. The DMN Northeast January 2018 monthly average price for cheddar blocks is $2.1032, compared to $2.2893 one year ago. Processed 5# sliced average price is $1.7365, compared to $1.9511 one year ago. At Tuesday’s CME Group trading, daily cash prices saw barrels closed at $1.3700, up $0.0500, and blocks closed at $1.5175, increased $0.0550 from last Tuesday. This week, a cooperative export assistance program accepted requests for export assistance to sell 2.974 million pounds (1,349 metric tons) of cheese. The DMN National Retail Report-Dairy, for February 2-8, 2018, noted the U.S. weighted average advertised price for 8 ounce cheese block was $2.10, decreased 18 cents from the previous week and down 5 cents from last year. The U.S. weighted average advertised price of 8 ounce cheese shreds was $2.18, decreased 9 cents from last week and down 5 cents from a year ago. Northeast region’s weighted average advertised price for 8 ounce cheese blocks was $2.17, 7 cents above the U.S. average, with a regional price range of $1.66-$3.00. The Southeast region’s average price for 8 oz. cheese blocks was $2.13, 3 cents above the average U.S. price, with a regional price range of $1.66-$3.50. In the Northeast, the average price for 8 oz. cheese shreds was $2.25, 7 cents above the national average. In the Southeast, the average price for 8 oz. shreds was $1.94, 24 cents lower than the U.S. average, with prices ranging $1.66-$2.50. DAIRY PRODUCTS: According to NASS, U.S. total cheese production in December 2017 was 1.09 billion pounds, 2.6 percent higher than a year ago and 3.0 percent higher than last month. In the Atlantic region, total cheese production was 139.2 million pounds, 6.2 percent higher than a year ago, but 0.6 percent lower than the previous month. Total cheese production and percentage change, from last year for selected Eastern states, are New York 77.7 million pounds, +8.3 percent; Pennsylvania 35.0 million pounds, +1.5 percent; Vermont 12.8 million pounds, +5.1 percent, and New Jersey 5.4 million pounds, +2.0 percent.

commodity narrative:
Northeastern U.S. Cheese Commentary:
Northeast cheese production is busy as milk continues to clear into vats. Milk availability is steady to tight as some cheese makers report they are receiving just enough loads for scheduled production levels. With the upcoming Super Bowl, domestic cheddar cheese block sales are up. Spot sale cheese trading activities are stable to light as prices on some indices are solid, however some market participants are content with their orders and do not need to purchase immediate loads. The Northeast wholesale cheddar and Muenster prices decreased $0.0125, but the process cheese price increased $0.0225. The Grade A Swiss price is steady. This week, a cooperative export assistance program accepted 25 requests for export assistance to sell 4.365 million pounds (1,982 metric tons) of cheese. At Tuesday’s CME Group trading, daily cash prices saw barrels closed at $1.3200, down $0.0450, and blocks closed at $1.4625, decreased $0.0975 from last Tuesday. The DMN National Retail Report-Dairy, for January 26-February 1, 2018, noted the U.S. weighted average advertised price for 8 ounce cheese block was $2.28, decreased 21 cents from the previous week, but up 23 cents from last year. The U.S. weighted average advertised price of 8 ounce cheese shreds was $2.27, down 13 cents from last week, but up 8 cents from a year ago. Northeast region’s weighted average advertised price for 8 ounce cheese blocks was $2.11, 17 cents below the U.S. average, with a regional price range of $1.67-$3.50. The Southeast region’s average price for 8 oz. cheese blocks was $2.40, 12 cents above the average U.S. price, with a regional price range of $1.99-$3.50. The Northeast average price for 8 oz. cheese shreds was $2.37, up 10 cents from the U.S. average price, with a regional price range of $1.88-$3.00. In the Southeast, the average price for 8 oz. shreds was $2.27, same price as the U.S. average, with prices ranging $1.99-$2.50. COLD STORAGE: According to NASS, U.S. stocks of total natural cheese as of December 31, 2017 totaled 1.3 billion pounds, 2 percent higher than the previous month, and up 7 percent from a year ago. Swiss cheese totaled 26.4 million pounds, 9 percent higher than a year ago, and up 6 percent from last month. In New England, stocks of American cheese totaled 67.7 million pounds, 6 percent higher than December 2016 and 7 percent higher than November 2017.
